answer:
We have to consider all the cases in which three points may lie on a line.  There are three points in the rightmost column, which lie on a line.  Likewise, there are three in the leftmost column.  Next, there are nine combinations of three points in the second row, of which four are collinear.  And there are four collinear combinations of three points in the top row.  The bottom row does not contain any collinear triples.  This gives us $3+3+4+3=13$ combinations of three points in which the three points lie on a line out of a total of $\binom{9}{3}=84$ combinations.  Hence, the desired probability is $\boxed{\frac{13}{84}}$.

