Let $\log(kx)=2\log(x+2)\iff\log k+\log x=2\log(x+2)\iff\log k=\log(x+2)^2-\log x=\log\left(\frac{(x+2)^2}{x}\right)\iff k=\frac{(x+2)^2}{x}=x+\frac{4}{x}+4$. This is one-to-one on $[-500,500]$, so it suffices to analyze $\frac{(x+2)^2}{x}=x+\frac{4}{x}+4$ on $[-500,500]$. Since $\frac{(x+2)^2}{x}>0$, we can ignore the sign of $x$ and analyze $\frac{(x+2)^2}{x}=x+\frac{4}{x}+4$ for $x\ge0$. Rearranging, we have $(x-2)^2=x^2+4x+4$, so $0=4x+4\iff x=-1$. Thus $x=-1$ is the only solution, so $-1$ is the only integer value of $k$ in the interval that satisfies the conditions. The answer is $\boxed{1}$.rray
If $k<0$, then $\log(kx)$ is not defined, so $k\ge0$. If $k>0$, the function $y=\log(kx)$ is increasing, while $y=2\log(x+2)$ is also increasing. They can only intersect at $x=-1$, so there is one solution in the interval if and only if $k=\frac{(x+2)^2}{x}=x+\frac{4}{x}+4$. Rearranging this gives us $x^2+4=0$, so $x=-2$. Substituting back gives $k=\boxed{0}$.rayt
